      <lg xml:id="MTA45">
<l>āmē yamarark kaṟiya vatuniṟka</l>
<l>nāmē yaṟikiṟpō naṉṉeñcē – pūmēya</l>
<l>mātavattōṉ ṟāḷpaṇinta vāḷarakka ṉīṇmuṭiyaip</l>
<l>pātamattā leṇṇiṉāṉ paṇpu</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>There are things not known to the immortals.<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">Here we may consider taking aṟiya not as the usual infinitive, but as a participial noun negative neuter plural, although the infinitive is likewise possible: “It is for the immortals to know.”</note> Let that rest.</l>
<l>We, we can know<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">The strange form aṟikiṟpōm gives rise to doubt as to whether to understand it as an intermittant formation of the not yet established present tense (for which the “correct” form would be aṟikiṉṟōm) or as a late survivor of the old auxiliary construction with kil-tal, “to be able to”; for parallels cf. Po. 56.3 kāṇkilāṉ, Pū. 16.4 pey-kiṟpār.</note> [them], good heart – [those] qualities of the one who counted</l>
<l>with [his] feet<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">Here instead of the instrumental form to be expected, pātattāl, we seem to have the usual oblique stem -attu added to, not replacing the noun ending -m of pātam. Tārkkatīrttar Rāmānujācāryar gives an alternative interpretation by glossing with appātattāl, that is, he suggests that for the sake of etukai the proclitic demonstrative pronoun a- is postpositioned and bearing the case suffix. One way or the other one would want parallels.</note> the tall heads of the Rākṣasa<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">Rāvaṇa in his youth spent years of doing penance to gain the favour of Brahmā, in the process cutting off his own head ten times, each time growing a new one, ending up with all ten heads restored to him, only to loose them all in the end to Rāma.</note> with a sword<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">The attribute vāḷ to arakkaṉ (the Tamilised form of Skt. rākṣasa-) occurs in all the three places that arakkaṉ is used in the Antāti-s (Po. 45.3, Pū. 52.3, Pē. 77.2), here and in Pēy clearly referring to Rāvaṇa, presumably all three referring to the episode described in the preceding note, which would make the sword the weapon Rāvaṇa used to cut off his own head.</note>  who had humbled</l>
<l>himself at the feet of the one with great penance who resides in the flower.</l>
      </lg>
    </div>
